@DATABASE AGgrep.guide
@NODE MAIN 
	
    AGgrep is an ARexx script which runs grep (a file search program)
    and puts the results in an AmigaGuide file. That way you can
    click on a line number where the search text was found, and your
    text editor is opened with the correct file at the correct line.
    
    I wrote it for use with TurboText and Grep (from SAS/C v6.3)
    
    @{" Installation " link Installation}
    
    Support Files:
        @{" DoArgs " link DoArgs} - uses a window with a string requester to ask
                    for arguments, then runs a program.
        @{" Grep.ttx " link grepttx} - A turbotext script to call AGgrep from
                    turbotext.
    
    @{" Author " link Author} - Brian Gragg          
                            
@ENDNODE

@NODE Installation "Installation"
    
    Put the files where ever you want.  Then edit the AGgrep.rexx file.  At 
    the start you will see the following:
    
    
        /* GREP CALL */
    GREPCALL = "sc:c/grep"          
        /* GREP HELP CALL */
    GREPHELP = "sc:c/grep ?"
        /* MACRO TO CALL YOUR EDITOR, ARGUMENT WILL BE FILE|LINENUM */
    EDITMACRO = "rexx:TTXEditAtLine.rexx"
        /* AMIGAGUIDE CALL */
    AMIGAGUIDE = "sys:utilities/amigaguide PUBSCREEN TURBOTEXT"
    
        
    you will need to edit them to point to your version of grep, the edit
    macro, and amigaguide.
    
    That should be it.  It makes two temporary files and puts them in t:
    as defined in the following lines: (Pragma("i") returns the task id
    so as to make the files usable on a multitasking system.)
            
    grepfile = "t:grep." || Pragma("i")
    agfile = "t:ttxgrep." || Pragma("i")
    
    
    To call your editor to open the file at the correct line number, you
    must supply a macro to do this.  I've included one for Turbotext
    called TTXEditAtLine.rexx.  As shown above, it's default location is
    in rexx:, but you can change it in the AGgrep.rexx file.
                
@ENDNODE

@NODE DoArgs "DoArgs Description"

    DoArgs is really just a front end for the rexxarplib.library 'Request' 
    function. 
    
    USAGE:  RX DoArgs x,y,prompt,string,canceltext,pubscreen,cmd
    
    x          - requester left edge
    y          - requester top edge
    prompt     - the prompt text
    string     - the default string to show in the requester
    canceltext - the text to show in the CANCEL button
    pubscreen  - a public screen name to open the requester on or (WORKBENCH)
    cmd        - the command to run after getting the arguments.
    
    EXAMPLE:  
    RX DoArgs 100,100,Enter Arguments,-$ mode #?,Cancel,,sys:rexxc/rx aggrep
    
    Which will open a window asking for arguments with a default of -$ mode #?
    and will send the response to aggrep.
    
@ENDNODE

@NODE Grepttx "Grep.ttx Description"

    Grep.ttx is a turbotext script you can link to a key, or call as amacro
    from TurboText (see the turbotext docs for how to do it).  It will ask
    you for your grep arguments and call AGgrep.rexx.
    
    It expects to find RX in your sys:rexxc directory (which is standard)
    and the AGgrep.rexx file in rexx:
    
    If it's somewhere else, just change the script.  Grep.ttx is only 4 lines
    long, so it's real simple.
    
@ENDNODE

